{
  "answer": "**Heliseus (Eleusius), the reeve of Nicomedia, first proposes marriage indirectly by wooing Juliana's father, Africanus, with gifts of treasure and \"words of promise\" to secure her as his wife.**[^1]\n\nThis occurs early in the poem (*Juliana*, chapter 1), after introducing the characters. The text describes his lustful desire and actions:\n\n> The reeve was inflamed, filled with a fire  \n> of lust for the maiden. He longed for her beauty,  \n> **and wished for her as his wife. He lavished her father  \n> with treasure and trinkets, with tokens of gold,  \n> and wooed the wealthy man with words of promise.**  \n> Her father agreed, enticed by the riches,  \n> and pledged his daughter to the powerful pagan.[^1]\n\nIn the Old English transliteration, this corresponds to lines describing his love kindling (\"tha his mod ongon faemnan lufian\") and the betrothal (\"tha waes sio faemne mid hyre faeder willan welegum biweddad\").[^2] The narrative briefly repeats this sequence later (e.g., p-06444b), but the initial instance is here.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, [p-6bc4fe](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-6bc4fe).\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, [p-01394b](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/transliteration/#p-01394b).\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Juliana*, [p-06444b](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-06444b).",
